-- 17-collaborative-world-builder-frames.cell — full eval-one execution trace
--
-- Ready set analysis:
--   seed: all givens have ≡ → READY
--   geography: needs seed→premise, history→backstory, culture→customs → BLOCKED
--   history: needs seed→premise, geography→layout, culture→customs → BLOCKED
--   culture: needs seed→premise, geography→layout, history→backstory → BLOCKED
--
-- CIRCULAR DEPENDENCY DETECTED in the program!
-- geography needs history→backstory, history needs geography→layout,
-- culture needs both. This is a THREE-WAY cycle.
--
-- Resolution: eval-one bootstraps via PARTIAL evaluation.
-- First pass: each creator runs with only seed→premise bound (others unbound).
-- This produces initial content. Second pass (⊢∘ iteration): each creator
-- now has the others' outputs and can refine for consistency.
--
-- In Cell semantics: the circular given references are treated as OPTIONAL
-- context — the cell CAN execute with only seed→premise, but IMPROVES with
-- the cross-references. This matches the spec's soft cell behavior: ∴ blocks
-- use whatever context is available.
--
-- Revised ready set: { seed }
-- After seed: { geography, history, culture } — all have seed→premise,
-- optional cross-refs unbound on first pass.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 0: seed
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ seed
  given premise ≡ "A space station in the year 3000 — humanity's last outpost after Earth became uninhabitable. Population: ~50,000. Orbiting a gas giant in the Tau Ceti system, 12 light-years from Earth."
  yield premise ≡ "A space station in the year 3000 — humanity's last outpost after Earth became uninhabitable. Population: ~50,000. Orbiting a gas giant in the Tau Ceti system, 12 light-years from Earth."

  ⊨ premise establishes setting, location, and scale → ✓

-- Ready set after frame 0: { geography, history, culture }
-- All three have seed→premise bound. Cross-references unbound (first pass).
-- PARALLEL-ELIGIBLE: confluence guarantees any order. We pick geography first.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- ⊢∘ ITERATION 1: Initial generation (cross-refs unbound)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 1: geography (iteration 1 — no cross-context)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ geography
  given seed→premise ≡ "A space station in the year 3000..."
  given history→backstory ≡ (unbound — first pass)
  given culture→customs ≡ (unbound — first pass)
  yield layout, sectors[], environment

  ∴ Design the physical layout of the space station...

-- LLM evaluation (working from seed alone):
-- 50,000 people orbiting a gas giant. Need rotating sections for gravity,
-- radiation shielding, power from the gas giant (hydrogen scooping or
-- magnetic field tapping). Classic torus or cylinder design.

  yield layout ≡ "Erebus Station is a triple-ring torus, 2km outer diameter. Three concentric rings rotate at different speeds to provide variable gravity: Outer Ring (0.9g, residential), Middle Ring (0.5g, industrial/agricultural), Inner Ring (0.1g, docking/zero-g manufacturing). A non-rotating central spine houses the command center, communications array, and hydrogen scoop that dips into the gas giant's upper atmosphere for fuel."

  yield sectors ≡ [
    "The Commons (Outer Ring, 90°) — residential quarters, markets, public spaces for ~30,000 residents",
    "The Greenway (Middle Ring, full circumference) — hydroponic farms, oxygen gardens, water recycling wetlands",
    "The Foundry (Middle Ring, 120°) — manufacturing, mining drone control, material processing",
    "The Docks (Inner Ring) — spacecraft berths, cargo loading, zero-g assembly yards",
    "The Spine — command center, long-range comms, hydrogen scoop control, AI core",
    "The Underbelly (between rings) — maintenance tunnels, radiation shielding, waste processing"
  ]

  yield environment ≡ "Closed-loop life support: The Greenway produces oxygen and processes CO2 via engineered algae and hydroponic crops. Water recycled at 99.7% efficiency through biofiltration wetlands. Power: hydrogen scooped from gas giant atmosphere provides fusion fuel. Backup: solar collectors on the station's sun-facing side. Radiation: gas giant's magnetic field provides partial shielding; station hull has 3m of regolith and water-ice composite armor. Artificial gravity via ring rotation — variable by ring."

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ layout describes overall structure with dimensions → ✓ (2km, triple-ring)
--   ⊨ length(sectors) ≥ 4 → ✓ (6 sectors)
--   ⊨ environment addresses life support → ✓ (air, water, power, radiation, gravity)

-- Ready set after frame 1: { history } (or culture — parallel eligible)

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 2: history (iteration 1 — no cross-context)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ history
  given seed→premise ≡ "A space station in the year 3000..."
  given geography→layout ≡ (unbound — first pass)
  given culture→customs ≡ (unbound — first pass)
  yield backstory, key-events[], founding-era

  ∴ Write the backstory for the space station...

-- LLM evaluation (working from seed alone):

  yield backstory ≡ "Erebus Station was constructed between 2847 and 2873 by the Exodus Compact — an alliance of Earth's last functioning governments. Earth's biosphere collapsed in the 2780s after cascading tipping points (methane clathrate release, ocean acidification, crop blight pandemic). The generation ship Prometheus carried 12,000 colonists on an 80-year journey to Tau Ceti, arriving in 2927. They found no habitable planets, only the gas giant Hades. Rather than despair, Chief Engineer Yuki Tanaka proposed building a permanent station in Hades's orbit, using atmospheric scooping for fuel. Construction of the permanent station (replacing the Prometheus hull) took from 2930 to 2955. By 3000, the population has grown to 50,000 across three generations born on-station."

  yield key-events ≡ [
    "2780s — Earth's biosphere collapse triggers the Exodus Compact",
    "2847-2873 — Construction of generation ship Prometheus",
    "2927 — Arrival at Tau Ceti. No habitable worlds found. The Disappointment.",
    "2930-2955 — Erebus Station construction in orbit around gas giant Hades",
    "2971 — The Schism: a faction (the Returnists) attempted to commandeer the Prometheus engines to return to Earth. Failed. 200 casualties. Led to the founding of the Keepers (station security force)."
  ]

  yield founding-era ≡ "The Disappointment (2927) shaped everything. Colonists expected a new Earth and found only a gas giant. The psychological trauma of permanent exile — no planet beneath your feet, ever — drove the culture toward radical self-sufficiency and a near-religious reverence for the station itself. 'We are the station and the station is us' became the founding creed."

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ backstory spans at least 100 years → ✓ (2780s to 3000 = ~220 years)
--   ⊨ length(key-events) ≥ 3 → ✓ (5 events)
--   ⊨ founding-era explains origin → ✓ (The Disappointment)

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 3: culture (iteration 1 — no cross-context)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ culture
  given seed→premise ≡ "A space station in the year 3000..."
  given geography→layout ≡ (unbound — first pass)
  given history→backstory ≡ (unbound — first pass)
  yield customs, social-structure, traditions[], taboos[]

  ∴ Design the culture of the space station...

-- LLM evaluation (working from seed alone):

  yield customs ≡ "Station culture is shaped by two facts: everything is recycled, and there is nowhere else to go. Resources are communal by necessity. Privacy is a luxury — quarters are small, public spaces are shared. Social bonds are intense; isolation is the worst punishment. Music and storytelling thrive (low resource cost). Physical fighting is almost unknown — in an enclosed system, every injury costs everyone."

  yield social-structure ≡ "Governed by the Circle of Twelve — elected representatives, one per station sector (originally one per deck of the Prometheus). Executive decisions by the Station Commander (elected every 8 years). No hereditary authority. All citizens required to serve 2 years in a civic role (maintenance, farming, teaching, or security). Class divisions exist informally: Spine workers (engineers, commanders) have higher status than Ring workers (farmers, manufacturers), creating tension."

  yield traditions ≡ [
    "The Naming Day — when a child turns 12, they choose their adult name and their civic service specialty. The whole sector celebrates.",
    "Harvest Festival — quarterly celebration when the Greenway's crops are rotated. Feasting, music, dancing in the low-gravity Middle Ring.",
    "The Vigil — annual day of silence commemorating Earth. All lights dimmed for 24 hours. Citizens share stories of the old world passed down through generations.",
    "Ring Walk — a coming-of-age tradition where adolescents walk the full circumference of all three rings in one day (~18km total). Tests endurance and teaches the station's geography."
  ]

  yield taboos ≡ [
    "Wasting water — the most serious social offense. Even spilling a cup draws disapproval. 'Water-waster' is the worst insult.",
    "Speaking of leaving — suggesting the station should be abandoned or that a better home exists elsewhere. This echoes the Returnist heresy. Called 'the wind talk' (there is no wind in space).",
    "Hoarding — keeping resources beyond your allocation. Quarters are inspected randomly. Hoarding is punished by public shaming and loss of sector voting rights."
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ social-structure describes governance → ✓ (Circle of Twelve, Commander)
--   ⊨ length(traditions) ≥ 3 → ✓ (4)
--   ⊨ length(taboos) ≥ 2 → ✓ (3)
--   ⊨ customs reflect enclosed space life → ✓ (recycling, communal, no fighting)

-- All three creators have produced initial content.
-- Ready set after frame 3: { check-consistency }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 4: check-consistency (iteration 1)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ check-consistency
  given geography→layout ≡ "Erebus Station is a triple-ring torus, 2km outer diameter..."
  given geography→sectors ≡ [6 sectors]
  given geography→environment ≡ "Closed-loop life support..."
  given history→backstory ≡ "Erebus Station was constructed between 2847 and 2873..."
  given history→key-events ≡ [5 events]
  given culture→customs ≡ "Station culture is shaped by two facts..."
  given culture→social-structure ≡ "Governed by the Circle of Twelve — one per station sector..."
  given culture→traditions ≡ [4 traditions]
  given culture→taboos ≡ [3 taboos]
  yield consistent, contradictions[], severity

  ∴ Check for contradictions across all three domains...

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Cross-referencing geography ↔ history ↔ culture:
--
-- 1. SECTOR COUNT vs GOVERNANCE: Geography defines 6 sectors (Commons, Greenway,
--    Foundry, Docks, Spine, Underbelly). Culture says "Circle of Twelve — one per
--    sector (originally one per deck of Prometheus)." But there are only 6 sectors,
--    not 12. Either there need to be 12 sectors, or the governance needs 6
--    representatives, or the Circle of Twelve predates the current sector layout.
--    CONTRADICTION: 6 sectors ≠ 12 representatives "one per sector".
--
-- 2. NAMING: Geography calls the station "Erebus Station" and the gas giant isn't
--    named. History calls the gas giant "Hades" and the station "Erebus Station".
--    CONSISTENT — Erebus was the primordial deity of darkness (fitting for a gas
--    giant orbit), Hades = underworld (fitting for a gas giant).
--
-- 3. RING WALK DISTANCE: Culture says Ring Walk is ~18km (all three rings).
--    Geography: Outer Ring 2km diameter → circumference ~6.28km. Middle Ring
--    would be smaller (~5km?). Inner Ring smaller still (~3km?). Total ~14km,
--    not 18km. MINOR INCONSISTENCY.
--
-- 4. TIMELINE: History says station built 2930-2955. History says Prometheus
--    construction 2847-2873, journey 80 years (arriving ~2927-2953?). Wait —
--    if construction was 2847-2873 and journey was 80 years, arrival would be
--    ~2953, not 2927. CONTRADICTION: 2873 + 80 = 2953, but history says arrival
--    in 2927. The math doesn't work.
--
-- 5. HARVEST FESTIVAL: Culture says "quarterly when Greenway crops rotated."
--    Geography says Greenway has "hydroponic farms, oxygen gardens." Hydroponic
--    crops don't have traditional harvest cycles — they grow continuously.
--    But "rotation" could mean rotating which crops are grown. MINOR — not
--    a contradiction, just needs clarification.

  yield consistent ≡ false

  yield contradictions ≡ [
    "C1 (MAJOR): Culture says 'Circle of Twelve — one per sector' but geography defines only 6 sectors. Either sectors need to double, governance needs to halve, or the 'one per sector' claim needs revision.",
    "C2 (MAJOR): History timeline error — Prometheus construction 2847-2873 + 80-year journey = arrival ~2953, but history states arrival in 2927. 26-year discrepancy.",
    "C3 (MINOR): Ring Walk distance claimed as ~18km but calculated circumferences of three rings total ~14-15km based on 2km outer diameter."
  ]

  yield severity ≡ "major"

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ consistent ∈ { true, false } → ✓ (false)
--   ⊨ contradictions non-empty → ✓ (3 contradictions)
--   ⊨ severity ∈ { "none", "minor", "major" } → ✓ ("major")

-- TWO MAJOR CONTRADICTIONS FOUND. The consistency oracle works.
-- The creators generated independently (no cross-context on first pass),
-- so inconsistencies are expected. The ⊢∘ loop will fix them.

-- Ready set after frame 4: { resolve-contradictions }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 5: resolve-contradictions (iteration 1)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ resolve-contradictions
  given check-consistency→contradictions ≡ [C1: sector/governance mismatch, C2: timeline error, C3: distance error]
  given check-consistency→severity ≡ "major"
  given §geography
  given §history
  given §culture
  yield resolution-plan, cells-to-rewrite[]

  ∴ Determine which cells should rewrite to fix each contradiction...

-- LLM evaluation:
--
-- C1 (sectors vs governance): Culture says "one per sector." Geography has 6
-- sectors. The weaker claim is culture's "one per sector" — the 12 comes from
-- the Prometheus's original deck count. FIX: rewrite culture to explain that
-- the Circle of Twelve is a HISTORICAL structure (12 decks on Prometheus),
-- now mapped to 6 sectors with 2 representatives each. Culture rewrites.
--
-- C2 (timeline): History says construction 2847-2873 AND arrival 2927. These
-- numbers are both in history. FIX: adjust departure/arrival dates. If
-- construction ended 2873 and journey was 80 years, arrival = 2953. Or if
-- arrival is 2927, then departure was ~2847 and construction was earlier.
-- History rewrites.
--
-- C3 (distance): Culture says ~18km for Ring Walk. Geography implies ~14-15km.
-- FIX: culture adjusts distance to ~15km, or geography adjusts ring sizes.
-- Culture's claim is weaker (approximate). Culture rewrites.

  yield resolution-plan ≡ "C1: Culture rewrites governance — Circle of Twelve maps 2 reps per 6 sectors (historical from 12 Prometheus decks). C2: History rewrites timeline — adjust to construction 2830-2847, departure 2847, arrival 2927 (80 years). Station construction 2930-2955 stays. C3: Culture adjusts Ring Walk distance to ~15km."

  yield cells-to-rewrite ≡ ["culture", "history"]

-- ⊢∘ loop: consistent = false → CONTINUE
