⊢= obs-circular-bootstrap
  given §17-collaborative-world-builder
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "CIRCULAR DEPENDENCIES BOOTSTRAP VIA PARTIAL EVALUATION: geography needs history, history needs geography, culture needs both. This is a three-way cycle that eval-one can't resolve via Kahn's algorithm. The solution: treat cross-references as OPTIONAL context. First pass: each creator works from the seed alone. Second pass: each creator sees the others' outputs. This is a TWO-PHASE BOOTSTRAP — generate independently, then refine collaboratively. Cell's soft cells (∴) handle this naturally because LLMs can work with partial context. Hard cells (⊢=) could not — they'd deadlock on unbound inputs."

⊢= obs-consistency-oracle-catches-real-bugs
  given §17-collaborative-world-builder
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "THREE REAL CONTRADICTIONS FOUND: (1) 6 sectors vs 12 governance seats — a structural mismatch between geography and culture, (2) timeline arithmetic error — history contradicted itself (2873 + 80 ≠ 2927), (3) physical distance error — culture claimed 18km, geometry says ~15km. These are EXACTLY the kind of bugs that plague collaborative writing: different authors assume different numbers. The consistency oracle is a CROSS-REFERENCE CHECKER that no individual creator can perform. Each creator's output is locally coherent but globally inconsistent."

⊢= obs-asymmetric-rewrites
  given §17-collaborative-world-builder
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "ONLY TWO OF THREE CREATORS REWROTE: geography was unchanged across both iterations. History and culture rewrote to match geography's physical constraints. This is the correct resolution: physical layout is the HARDEST constraint (you can't change the laws of physics), so softer domains (narrative history, social customs) yield. The resolve-contradictions cell applied this logic: 'the cell with the weaker claim yields.' Physics > history > culture in constraint strength. This mirrors real collaborative world-building: you set the map first, then write the history to fit."

⊢= obs-convergence-in-two
  given §17-collaborative-world-builder
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "CONVERGED IN 2 ITERATIONS: iteration 1 generated independently (3 contradictions). Iteration 2 fixed all three with targeted rewrites. No iteration 3 needed. This fast convergence happened because the contradictions were MECHANICAL (wrong numbers, mismatched counts), not CONCEPTUAL (disagreement about tone, theme, or direction). Conceptual contradictions — 'the culture feels too dark for the history' — would require more iterations and subtler oracle judgments. The program demonstrated the easy case. Harder: a culture cell that generates customs contradicting the SPIRIT of the history, not just the facts."

⊢= obs-world-building-as-constraint-satisfaction
  given §17-collaborative-world-builder
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "WORLD-BUILDING IS CONSTRAINT SATISFACTION: the three creators are constraint GENERATORS (each adds facts), and the consistency oracle is a constraint CHECKER. The ⊢∘ loop is constraint PROPAGATION — resolve violations until fixpoint. This maps exactly to CSP (constraint satisfaction problems). Cell's contribution: the constraints are SEMANTIC (does the culture make sense given the history?), not just syntactic (do the numbers match). The LLM oracle can check semantic consistency that no formal verifier can. This is Cell's fusion property: classical checking (timeline arithmetic) + semantic checking (cultural coherence) in the same oracle."
